
What is Docker?
Docker is a tool that allows developers to pack their applications with all the necessary parts (libraries, dependencies) into a single unit called a Container. This ensures the app runs the same on every machine.

Key Concepts I Learned Today:

Dockerfile: A simple text file with instructions on how to build a Docker image.

Docker Image: A read-only template (recipe) used to create containers.

Docker Container: A running instance of an image.

Docker Hub: A place where we can find and share Docker images.

Commands I Used:

docker build -t my-app . - To create an image from a Dockerfile.

docker images - To list all the images on my laptop.

docker run my-app - To start a container from an image.

docker rmi [image-id] - To remove an image.
